This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with the problem of crowd counting, which is a common task in computer vision. The paper also extensively employs Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), which are widely used in computer vision tasks. 

The paper also involves the use of statistical networks to estimate mutual information between columns, which suggests that it may belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

The use of mutual learning schemes and asynchronous parameter update processes further supports the possibility of this paper belonging to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. 

The paper's focus on improving generalization ability through reducing parameter redundancy suggests that it may also belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper's use of multi-column networks and its focus on improving feature representation suggests that it may also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
